{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 09:58:05.320427", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and goal\n- Topology: 1 super-spine (AS 65000), 2 spines (AS 65100 and 65101), 2 leaves (AS 65200 and 65201), 2 hosts (10.0.0.2 and 10.0.1.2).\n- Data plane address plan: hosts on 10.<pod>.<leaf>.0/24; inter-router links are 172.16.0.0/16 /31s.\n- Control plane: pure eBGP on all routers (FRR).\n\n1) End-to-end reachability and latency\n- Host-to-host ping:\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 0% loss, avg RTT ~3.28 ms.\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: 0% loss, avg RTT ~2.45 ms.\nAssessment: Forwarding between leaves across the spine/super-spine fabric is functioning with low latency and no loss.\n\n2) Control-plane health (BGP)\n- All BGP sessions are established on all routers.\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) peers with 65100 (172.16.0.4) and 65101 (172.16.0.8); receives 1 prefix from each, advertises its 10.0.0.0/24.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201) peers with 65100 (172.16.0.6) and 65101 (172.16.0.10); receives 1 prefix from each, advertises its 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100) peers with super-spine (172.16.0.0) and both leaves; receives routes from both leaves; shows 0 prefixes received from super-spine.\n  - spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101) peers with super-spine (172.16.0.2) and both leaves; receives routes from leaves and 2 prefixes from super-spine.\n  - super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000) peers with both spines; has both /24s with two paths each via the two spines.\n\n- BGP RIB snapshots of interest:\n  - super_spine_router_0 selects, for both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24, the path via spine_router_0_0 (172.16.0.1). As a result, it advertises both prefixes to spine_router_0_1 and none to spine_router_0_0 (standard BGP behavior: do not send a route back to the neighbor it was learned from when that path is currently the best).\n  - spine_router_0_1 sees multiple paths per prefix:\n    - Direct from the corresponding leaf (best, shortest AS path 65200/65201).\n    - Via super-spine (path contains 65000).\n    - Also via the other leaf (paths like 65201 65100 65200), indicating leaves are re-advertising non-local routes.\n  - spine_router_0_0 shows best paths via each leaf and no additional alternatives from super-spine (consistent with receiving 0 prefixes from the super-spine for these routes).\n\nAssessment: BGP control-plane is converged and consistent with observed data-plane reachability. All intended networks are present in the fabric.\n\n3) Notable findings and anomalies\n\nA. Asymmetric advertisement from super-spine to spines\n- Observation: spine_router_0_0 shows 0 prefixes received from super-spine; spine_router_0_1 receives 2.\n- Localization: super_spine_router_0 best-path selection prefers spine_router_0_0 as next-hop for both /24s; therefore, per standard BGP behavior, super-spine does not advertise those routes back to spine_router_0_0, but does advertise them to spine_router_0_1.\n- Root cause: Deterministic best path/tie-break at super-spine selecting the neighbor 172.16.0.1 (spine_router_0_0) for both /24s. This is expected protocol behavior, not a fault.\n\nB. Leaves acting as transit and re-advertising non-local routes\n- Observation: On spine_router_0_1, extra longer-path routes (e.g., 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.11 with AS path 65201 65100 65200) indicate that leaf_router_0_1 is re-advertising a route learned from spine_router_0_0. Symmetric behavior is implied for the other prefix/leaf.\n- Localization: leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) and leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201).\n- Root cause: Leaves have “no bgp ebgp-requires-policy” and no route-maps/filtering, allowing them to advertise EBGP-learned routes to other EBGP neighbors. In a typical Clos with EBGP, leaves are configured as non-transit; here they are inadvertently providing transit between spines, resulting in additional (longer) paths in the network. While this does not break connectivity, it deviates from common Clos design intent and can lead to unnecessary path options.\n\nC. Session uptime\n- Observation: BGP sessions show short uptimes (~00:00:37) at the time of inspection.\n- Assessment: Consistent with recent startup of the lab environment. No instability indicated (no flaps observed).\n\n4) Overall assessment\n- Data plane: Healthy. Host-to-host connectivity is normal with low RTT and no loss.\n- Control plane: All BGP adjacencies established; routing tables contain expected leaf /24s end-to-end.\n- Abnormal/Non-ideal behavior detected:\n  - Leaves are re-advertising non-local routes (providing transit), which is atypical for a non-transit leaf design in Clos fabrics.\n- No immediate service impact detected from the above; behavior explains the presence of extra paths on spines and the asymmetric advertisements from the super-spine.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 6287, "output_tokens": 7339, "total_tokens": 13626, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 5248}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 6016}}}
